\begin_layout Subsection
Proof of Sequential Multiplicativity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{i}(\hat{O})$
\end_inset

 refer to the outcome of measuring an operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{O}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 parametrizes the sequence of the measurement.
 Sequential multiplicativity is the statement that 
\begin_inset Formula $m(\hat{P})=m_{1}(\hat{P}_{1})m_{2}(\hat{P}_{2})=m_{1}(\hat{P}_{2})m_{2}(\hat{P}_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 The proof is simple.
 Consider a set of compatible operators, which are also complete.
 For simplicity, let's say the set is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\{\hat{P}_{1},\hat{P}_{2}\}$
\end_inset

 (not anti-commutation, its a set).
 Now consider the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}=\hat{P}_{1}+\hat{P}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 be s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}\left|\psi\right\rangle =p\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\nexists$
\end_inset

 any 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}_{i}\left|\psi\right\rangle =\lambda_{i}\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 (else the result we're trying to prove will be trivial; as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is a simultaneous eigenket of 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, with eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}p_{2}$
\end_inset

).
 If you're uncomfortable with this `claim' or its relevance, one can use
 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1}=\sigma_{x}\otimes\sigma_{y}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{2}=\sigma_{y}\otimes\sigma_{x}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\sigma_{z}\otimes\sigma_{z}$
\end_inset

.
 Now, the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|00\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 makes for a non-trivial 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 Coming to the proof, first we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}_{i}\left|p_{1},p_{2}\right\rangle =p_{i}\left|p_{1},p_{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 note that it suffices for me to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 must be a superposition of only those simultaneous eigenkets 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|p_{1},p_{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}p_{2}=p$
\end_inset

.
 This can be proved as follows.
 Consider 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned} & \hat{P}\left|\psi\right\rangle  & = & p\left|\psi\right\rangle \\
\implies\left\langle p_{1},p_{2}\right|\hat{P}\left|\psi\right\rangle  & =p_{1}p_{2}\left\langle p_{1},p_{2}|\psi\right\rangle  & = & p\left\langle p_{1},p_{2}|\psi\right\rangle .
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

It follows immediately, that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle p_{1},p_{2}|\psi\right\rangle \neq0$
\end_inset

, then it entails that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|p_{1},p_{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 as an eigenket in its superposition, and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}p_{2}=p$
\end_inset

.
 However, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle p_{1},p_{2}|\psi\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset

, then we won't ever see 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}$
\end_inset

 as outcomes, so it is irrelevant.
 That then completes the proof.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

This can be readily generalized to any number of operators, even if they're
 not complete (in which case the remaining operators maybe added to complete
 the set, but the eigenvalues corresponding to them, don't play any role
 in the proof, and thus making its extension trivial).
